# Multi-tier-App-Jenkins-CICD:

› Usable elements -> AWS + EKS(K8S) + Docker + DockerHub + Maven + Git + Jenkins
› Create a new VPC
› Create private and public subnets
› Create InternetGateWay and NatGateWay 
› Create RDS MySQL inside the same VPC(private)
› Create Jenkins Ec2 server in public subnet
› Install Jenkins, Docker, kubectl, aws CLI on Ec2
› Connect Jenkins —> EKS —> RDS 

*Sign in to AWS Web Console

# VPC Creation Steps :

› VPC name : multi-tier-cicd-vpc  
› CIDR Range : 10.0.0.0/16
› 4 subnets —> 2 public subnets and 2 private subnets
› public-subnet-a(10.0.1.0/24) and public-subnet-b(10.0.2.0/24)
› private-subnet-a(10.0.3.0/24) and private-subnet-b(10.0.4.0/24)
› Edit VPC settings : Enable DNS hostname
› IGW (Internet Gateway) : multi-tier-cicd-IGW
› Attach IGW to multi-tier-cicd-vpc (for Accessibility)
› Go to Route table 
› Rename the pc associated route table to public-route-table
› Select Routes —> Edit Routes —> All Traffic(0.0.0.0) to IGW (multi-tier-cicd-IGW) 
› Now go to the subnet associations 
› Edit subnet associations and attach both public subnets —> Save Association
› NAT Gateway : multi-tier-cicd-NGW
› Availability Mode : Zonal
› Subnet : public-subnet-a
› Allocate public ip > Create Nat Gateway
› Create a Route Table : private-route-table
› Edit Routes : 0.0.0.0 > Nat Gateway
› Edit Subnet Assoiations : Add both private subnets (a and b)
› So,by now VPC has been fully configured

# Cluster Creation Steps :

› We can either use an EC2 instance and install dependencies like kubectl ,eksctl and aws-cli or, we can directly create a cluster
› Open Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service
› Cluster > Create Cluster 
› Configuration : Custom Configuration
› Name : crmeks
› Cluster Configuration : Latest recommended
› Role : AmazonEKSAutoClusterRole (Create if not present)
› Next, VPC : multi-tier-cicd-vpc
› Subnets : public-subnet-a and public-subnet-b
› Security Group : default
› Cluster Endpoint Access : Public
› Next, Keep default
› Next , Keep Default add EBS CSI only
› Next, Next, Preview and Create Cluster which will take some time 

# AWS-RDS Configuration Steps :

› Go to Subnet Groups and Create a DB Subnet Group : crm-db-subnet-group
› Availability zones : ap-south-1a and ap-south-b
› subnets : private-subnet-a and private-subnet-b
› Go to Amazon RDS
› Databases > Create Database
› Engine : MySQL
› Templates : dev/test
› Availability and durability : Single A-Z
› Db-instance-identifier : crm-mysql
› Master-username : crmuser
› Password : generic-password
› Allocated Storage : 20
› VPC : multi-tier-cicd-vpc
› Subnet-group : crm-db-subnet-group
› VPC-Security-group : Create New : rds-sg
› Create database


# Jenkins-Server-Creation Steps:

› Go to Ec2 > Launch Instance : jenkins-server
› AMI : ubuntu
› Instance Type : t3.medium
› key-pair : as per choice
› VPC : multi-tier-cicd-vpc
› subnet : public-subnet-a
› Auto Assign Public IP : Enable
› Security Group > Create Security Group > crm-sg
› ADD : 8080 , 50000
› Create Instance
› Connect to this Jenkins-machine

› We have to install the following in jenkins-server
~ java, jenkins, docker, kubectl, aws-cli (Use Ai Tools for installation help)
› Connect to the Jenkins Server 
› and perform installation of suggested 
› Configure New password and other setup requiremnts

# EKS Node Groups Creation :

*These are basically the worker node configurations
› By now, our EKS cluster is active
› Click on created cluster i.e ekscrm
› Under Compute tab we have Node groups
› Clock on “Add”
› Name : crmnodes
› Node IAM role : Create and Add , Next
› Node Group Scaling  Desired : 2 , Min : 1 , Max : 3 , Next
› Subnets : private-subnet-a and private-subnet-b
› Next and Create

# MySql Db Configuratons in Jenkins-VM:

› By now our database is ready for use
› We have to enable MySQL/Aurora and All Traffic inbound rules for Jenkins - Server
› Next up, we have to install MySQL client in Jenkins VM
› Copy database endpoint 
› Connect to MySQL Database as :
› mysql -h <database-endpoint> -u crmuser -p
› Enter your password and we’ll be in a Sql Environment configuring our DB
› We had created an RDS-SG which needs to have MYSQL/Aurora or All Traffic as an inbound security rule

› Connect to VM and hit the following command:

CREATE DATABASE mydb;

USE mydb;

CREATE TABLE customers (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,
    first_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    last_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    city VARCHAR(100),
    PRIMARY KEY (id)
);

› We’ll be using an application from the GitHub as : https://github.com/Haider7214/springboot-fullstack
› We’ll be cloning this to our repo and we’ll have to make changes in the deployment.yml for the db endpoint as jdbc:mysql://<database-endpoint>:3306/mydb

